<doc id="1058833" wikidata="Q1780921" url="?curid=1058833" title="Orthogonal complement">
<text>In the mathematical fields of linear algebra and functional analysis, the orthogonal complement of a subspace formula_1 of a vector space formula_2 equipped with a bilinear form formula_3 is the set formula_4 of all vectors in formula_2 that are orthogonal to every vector in formula_1. Informally, it is called the perp, short for perpendicular complement. It is a subspace of formula_2.

==Example==

Let formula_8 be the vector space equipped with the usual dot product formula_9 (thus making it an inner product space), and let formula_10 with
formula_11
then its orthogonal complement formula_12 can also be defined as formula_13 being
formula_14

The fact that every column vector in formula_15 is orthogonal to every column vector in formula_16 can be checked by direct computation. The fact that the spans of these vectors are orthogonal then follows by bilinearity of the dot product. Finally, the fact that these spaces are orthogonal complements follows from the dimension relationships given below.

== General bilinear forms ==
Let formula_2 be a vector space over a field formula_18 equipped with a bilinear form formula_19 We define formula_20 to be left-orthogonal to formula_21, and formula_21 to be right-orthogonal to formula_20, when formula_24 For a subset formula_1 of formula_26 define the left-orthogonal complement formula_4 to be
formula_28

There is a corresponding definition of the right-orthogonal complement. For a reflexive bilinear form, where formula_29, the left and right complements coincide. This will be the case if formula_3 is a symmetric or an alternating form.

The definition extends to a bilinear form on a free module over a commutative ring, and to a sesquilinear form extended to include any free module over a commutative ring with conjugation.

